natural problem:
Let  \begin{align*}
f(x) &= 2x + 5 \\
g(x) &= \sqrt{f(x)} - 2 \\
h(x) &= f(g(x))
\end{align*} What is $h(2)$?

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x :: real and f g h :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. f x = 2 * x + 5"
and h1 : "\<forall> x. g x = sqrt (f x) - 2"
and h2 : "\<forall> x. h x = f (g x)"
shows  "h 2 = 7"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Let  \begin{align*}
f(x) &= 2x + 5 \\
g(x) &= \sqrt{f(x)} - 2 \\
h(x) &= f(g(x))
\end{align*} What is $h(2)$? The final Answer is 7
 ### Proof
 Substituting, $h(2) = f(g(2))$.
 Now, $$g(2) = \sqrt{f(2)} - 2 = \sqrt{2 \cdot 2 + 5} - 2 = 3 - 2 = 1.$$ Thus, $$h(2) = f(g(2)) = f(1) = 2 \cdot 1 + 5 = \boxed{7}.$$
 *)
